Anonymous Fri 04 Sep 2020 21:09:05 No.32582940 Report
Quoted By: >>32583691
Guess I'll repost since that thread's running at zimzam speeds.

>>32582309
Lulls and grooves. Free writing is very much a "strike while the iron's hot" kinda deal; thing is, that impetus overlaps with the brainstorming you'll do to flesh out the details of your setting, plot, and characters. You'll hit lulls where things feel slow-rolling, and lose motivation entirely for a short time, but if you still keep your worldbuilding at the forefront of your mind's eye (easy for dreamy types as a consistent form of escapism from hum-drum tasks, daily monotonies, and those moments where you just breathe), you'll begin to adapt to thinking of it less as a story and more an account od something tangible you REALLY need to share. Skill doesn't factor into that in any way, only habit, experience, and practice really modify the ease with which your writing groove comes and goes. If you're the type who's had paracosms active in your imagination for a decade or two, this will come easier for you, I promise. It's how I was discovered years ago; I didn't even know I could do more than daydream, let alone do it above a sophomoric level. If you're fresh, then there's simply no time like the present to start; enjoy your worldbuilding, and it'll become an omnipresent activity playing within your mind, even when you're not thinking about it. Enjoy, enjoy, enjoy, I always say - have fun, and if you already have technical skill, you'll be driven to research techniques that will aid you in giving real life and sensuality into your world and your characters. Again, I can promise you that much. Whether or not you write at all, though, is entirely up to you. Just remember that motivation isn't everything - just doing it is key.
Anonymous

When I do openings you need to ask yourself what you're trying to convey.

Why start in the action? Use it to establish who the characters are and what they are doing. Use it to establish the setting beyond the action.

What weapons are used? How are they using them?

Of course this is just hypothesis, I don't know what you're writing but overall. Intros need to tell the reader:
-what's happening
and
-who's happening

Overall, an intro sets up the story and gets the reader interested.
